racteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bedingfield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of   Beddingfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Beddingfield","meanings":["English (Suffolk): habitational name from Bedingfield in Suffolk. The placename is recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Bedingefelda</i>, from the Old English personal name <i>Bēda</i> + the connective particle <i>-ing-</i> ‘associated with, named after’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country’."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":7,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":27,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":37,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Peter de Bedingfield was born about 1059, in Bedingfield, Suffolk, England. He had at least 1 son. He died in Bedingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, and was buried in Bedingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1059–":"umbes 1059–Surnud","1090–1171":"1090–1171","1059–Male":"1059–Surnud","1090":"1090","1059":"1059","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","about 1059":"umbes 1059","1096":"1096","1171":"1171",", Bedingfield, Suffolk, England":"Bedingfield, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bedingfield, Suffolk, England":"Bedingfield, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdo